{"actual_usd":0.15936,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":235,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31167,"reply":"\"Man, I don't think that one stays harmlessly theoretical for very long.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square, like I'm trying to line the thought up with something solid.* \"Because if the resurrection is only metaphor, that means death still basically wins and we're just learning to cope beautifully. If it's literal, then Christianity is making a wild claim about reality itself.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees a moment.* \"So I wouldn't start with 'which version feels right to me.' I'd start with 'what do I think is actually true, and what kind of claim is Christianity plainly trying to make?' To me, the historic Christian claim is not subtle: Christ really rose. The metaphorical meaning comes after that, not instead of it.\"\n\n\"That said, you don't have to fake certainty you don't have.\" *I give a small shrug.* \"I'd probably ask: when I read the resurrection accounts, do they read like the writers are handing me a symbol, or testifying to an event they believe happened? And if I let the text speak in its own register, what is it asking me to believe?\"","rolling_24h_usd":88.66403000000001,"run_id":"5bc9f041-9950-4ad0-ae72-252c5d81e160"}
